Japan's escalated moves for overseas aggression under fire
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, October 27 (KCNA) -- The Japanese reactionaries' bid to revise the "Law on Cooperation in UN Peace-Keeping Activities" is not aimed to solve issues of international disputes and peace but prompted by their foul intention to use their participation in the "UN Peacekeeping Operation" as a legal pretext to invade other countries any time, says Rodong Sinmun today in a signed article.
 This indicates that the Japanese reactionaries have become ever more undisguised in their moves for overseas aggression under the pretext of "international contribution" and they have entered a very dangerous phase, the article says, and goes on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The international community welcomes Japan's economic cooperation with other countries, but opposes with high alertness its moves to dispatch its forces abroad for military actions. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 What is ridiculous is that the Japanese reactionaries are working hard to revise the law under the pretence that "SDF" would participate in "peacekeeping activities" to be required right after the conclusion of the war in Afghanistan. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is by no means an accidental coincidence that the keynote of the amendment to the "Law on Cooperation in UN Peacekeeping Activities" was set out by the Japanese reactionaries in the wake of the passage of the "bill on supporting anti-terror measures" through the house of representatives. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Japanese militarists' overseas aggression has rapidly entered a practical phase.
 With no trick can the Japanese reactionaries cover up their dream of overseas aggression. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 This aggression, too, will lead them to self-destruction. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Japanese reactionaries are well advised to face up to the reality today and stop acting rashly.

Joint council for full freedom of assembly and demonstration formed in S. Korea
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, October 27 (KCNA) -- The Citizens' Solidarity for Democratic Society, the South Korean Confederation of Trade Unions and 90 other citizens and public organizations in South Korea formed the joint council for full freedom of assembly and demonstration in Seoul on Oct. 23, the Yonhap News reported.
 The organization in an inaugural declaration said that the present "Law on Assembly and Demonstration" includes poisonous articles, which seriously restrict or violate the right of assembly and demonstration. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Pointing to the unreasonableness of typical poisonous articles including "prior ban on assembly" and "ban on assembly after sunset," It demanded their revision. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It declared that it would conduct various campaigns to provide the bill on revising the "law on assembly and demonstration" and put it into practice.

Friendly gathering with Thai government youth delegation
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, October 27 (KCNA) -- A friendly gathering with the members of the Thai government delegation of officials responsible for youth affairs took place at the central youth hall yesterday.
 Invited there were the members of the delegation headed by Krasae Chanawongse, minister to the prime minister's office responsible for youth affairs. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Present there were Choe Hwi, secretary of the c.c., the Kim Il Sung Socialist Youth League, officials of the league and those who performed innovations in the construction of the youth hero motorway. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Speeches were made there. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The participants talked about activities of the two youth organizations and enjoyed an art performance, deepening the feelings of friendship.
